# Overseer review — {{FEATURE}}

You can fill in findings two ways under the section below — pick whichever is convenient:

**Plain sentences (easiest).** Just type each finding as a sentence or short paragraph under `## Implementation Review`. Examples:

```
The tabs component in src/app/dashboard/_components/tabs.tsx should be a generic component and moved to a more common folder.

Cancel button on the payment screen needs a confirmation dialog before submitting.
```

When you type `/mo-continue`, the millwright will read every freeform paragraph, classify its severity (blocker/major/minor) and scope (fix/re-implement/re-plan/re-spec), and rewrite it as a `### IR-NNN` block. You can edit the resulting blocks afterwards if the millwright's classification is off — the original wording is preserved verbatim in the block's `details:` body.

**Structured blocks (precise).** Write the finding directly in canonical form so the millwright skips classification:

```
### IR-NNN — <one-line summary>
- severity: blocker | major | minor
- scope:    fix | re-implement | re-plan | re-spec
- status:   open
- details: |
    multi-line context
- fix-note: (leave empty; the review session fills this in when resolved)
```

Both formats may coexist in the same file. The id (`IR-NNN`) is auto-assigned in the order the millwright canonicalizes; pre-existing structured ids are preserved.

**Scope guide** — pick the smallest rework that genuinely addresses the finding. The brainstorming review session reads this as a hint and decides the actual approach:

- `fix` — a patch to existing code (typo, missing edge case, minor logic). No chain re-entry.
- `re-implement` — the implementation diverged from requirements; the chain re-runs `executing-plans` for the affected sections.
- `re-plan` — the chain's plan was wrong or incomplete; the chain re-runs `writing-plans` (cascades through `executing-plans`).
- `re-spec` — the chain's spec/design is wrong; the chain re-runs `brainstorming` (cascades through `writing-plans` and `executing-plans`). Use sparingly — this invalidates the current implementation.

If you leave `scope:` out, the brainstorming session will classify it before acting.

**How the loop works:** when you type `/mo-continue`, the workflow invokes `/mo-review`, which launches a brainstorming review session with your open findings. The chain addresses them, asks you for approval, and exits when you reply `approve`. If you want another pass, add new `### IR-NNN` blocks to this file mid-session and reply `go again` instead — the chain will re-read this file and process the new findings.

Leave the section empty to approve with no findings. When done, type `/mo-continue`.

